properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Wintry weather expected for parts of Nova Scotia today and tonight. A low pressure system currently over the region will track east of the province this afternoon. Colder air will move in behind this system. As the colder air arrives the rain will turn to periods of snow. Snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 centimetres are expected with higher amounts possible over higher terrain. As this will be the first significant snowfall across parts of the province, the travelling public are urged to use caution and prepare for winter driving conditions. In addition there is a possibility of black ice on some roads late this afternoon into this evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall and poor driving conditions continue today. Total snowfall: near 15 cm except locally up to 25 cm over higher terrain. Locations: Corner Brook and vicinity, Gros Morne, Deer Lake - Humber Valley, Green Bay - White Bay, west of Grand Falls-Windsor and Buchans. Time span: continuing until this evening. Remarks: Snowfall accumulations are likely to vary considerably with the highest amounts expected from Badger to Buchans, northern sections of the Burgeo highway, Green Bay - White Bay and higher elevations between Deer Lake and Corner Brook and Deer Lake and Gros Morne. Areas near the coast and in lower lying areas through the Humber Valley are likely to see much lower amounts. The snow will taper off this evening but flurries, snow squalls, and strong westerly winds will develop again early Saturday along the west coast and persist through Saturday night. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A Pacific frontal system will move into the northern BC interior Friday morning. This system will be followed by an Arctic front pushing through the region Friday afternoon and then stalling over the region on Saturday. Long periods of snow are expected with total snowfall amounts of 30 to 40 cm forecast by Saturday evening. The heaviest snowfall is expected on Friday night and Saturday. Gusty winds behind the Arctic front may also give reduced visibilities in blowing snow starting Friday night. The snow will taper to flurries on Saturday evening. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
